Project Name: Sand Dune Restoration at Picnic Island Park
Project Description: The Sand Dune Restoration Project at Picnic Island Park was completed this past quarter. There were 100 volunteers who came out to Picnic Island Park to assist in creating this sand dune. Volunteers moved and positioned 180 cubic yards of sand and installed 3,310 native dune plants. Plants included: 576 2” Sea Purslane, 250 1-Gallon Dune Sunflower, 250 1-Gallon Muhly Grass, 250 1-Gallon Beach Elder, 250 1-Gallon Sand Cordgrass, 294 4” Sand Cordgrass, and 1,440 (4" LN)-2-N Sea Oats.
Habitat Description: Picnic Island Park is a coastal island with recreational opportunities. Coastal shrub and dunes are comprised of a variety of native species including: false-willow, railroad vine, milkweed, and white and red mangroves. The island has experienced extensive erosion.

Project Description: Implementation of a series of shoreline treatments per the USACE and NOAA's Systems Approach to Geomorphic Engineering (SAGE) method. Habitat Description: Dominant natural communities include pine flatwoods, scrubby flatwoods, scrub, freshwater marsh, and hardwood hammock. Southern marsh retains water after rains and slowly releases into the Myakka River.

Project Description: Copeland Park Pond Restoration community center and swimming pool complex, restrooms, playground areas, and several parking areas.  The project is located in the Hillsborough Bay watershed, and is an inland pond as a result of an old sinkhole. The pond has endured silt build-up over the years from runoff and has been invaded with non-native plant species. Project Name: Sun City Center Nature Trail Invasives Control
Project Description: Eradication of invasive exotic species within a 15-acre tract. Invasives included water hyacinth, Japanese climbing fern, cogon grass, ear pod tree, carrotwood, Peruvian primrose, and Brazilian pepper. Treatment of the banks of the canal at the approach to the trail entry point consisted of foliar spraying and then manual cutting/mowing the dead vegetation. A large number of exotic trees up to 6 inches dbh, mostly carrot wood and camphor, were removed and the stumps were treated with herbicide. Larger trees were girdled and treated. The chemicals Triclopyr and glyphosate were depending on what was being sprayed.

Project Description: Installation of new oyster shell bars and circular oyster beds along the southwestern shoreline of McKay Bay using mesh bags filled with fossilized oyster shell. The project’s goal is to create a greater surface area for settling oyster larvae, create habitat niches for other benthic organisms, and improve long-term water quality conditions through natural biological filtration services that oyster provide. The project will also benefit the Tampa Bay community by promoting environmental stewardship while offering hands-on opportunities to participate in Tampa Bay habitat restoration activities.
Habitat Description: McKay Bay is an ecologically important estuary located in the heart of a heavily industrialized area in the City of Tampa that has provided habitat to over 200 bird species. The project will occur in an area where seagrasses have been lost due to decreased water clarity associated with nutrient over-enrichment prior to 1980 and many years of developmental impacts, including dredge and fill activities, urban and industrial stormwater runoff, & industrial contamination.

Salterns, are rare habitats. These
special spots require a delicate balance of
salt water, sand, and a very specific

Salterns (also called salinas, salt flats, and
salt barrens) are open areas where tidal
waters pool and salt is concentrated
through evaporation.

Project Description: Invasive Species Control project of 1200 acres located on MacDill Air Force Base.  There are large tracts of land within the site that have been historically disturbed (former landfill areas) which are highly invaded with Brazilian pepper.  Chemical treatment for maintenance control of Brazilian pepper, lead tree, melaleuca, Australian pine throughout 1,300 acres on the eastern half of the base. Invasive grasses were treated through foliar application, and the tree species were primarily treated through basal bark application to kill the plants in place. Following initial herbicide applications, contractors were responsible to retreat invasive plant species within the project area.
Habitat Description: Pine forest areas are largely historic planted pine which has not been managed for timber. Areas of oak hammock and mangrove lined ditches are scattered throughout the pine areas and mangrove estuary predominates along the southern boundary of the site.  There are large tracts of land within the site that have been historically disturbed (former landfill areas) which are highly invaded with Brazilian pepper.
Project Benefits: Improve or protect water quality:Protect/improve/provide habitat for other wildlife

Project Name: Bower Tract Non-native plant removal and control
Project Description: The 167 acre Bower Tract Non-native plant removal and control project in Hillsborough County is intended to remove and control non-native and nuisance plants using a variety of methods. The project area includes coastal uplands, mangroves, intact and ditched, mangrove and upland islands, salt barrens and fresh water wetlands. There were 10 large ear pod trees on the eastern berm of Channel A that were cut down and all biomass removed from the site. Stumps were treated with herbicide to prevent re-sprouting. A skid steer with a forestry mulcher was used to clear non-native vegetation on the western Channel A berm and on the firelanes in the uplands. Areas were then treated with herbicide.
Habitat Description: The project area includes coastal uplands, mangroves, intact and ditched, mangrove and upland islands, salt barrens and fresh water wetlands. The site is bisected by Channel A which includes the manmade channel berms. These habitats are primarily in a healthy condition with scattered non-native vegetation occurring throughout the site.

Project Description: Chemical treatment for maintenance control of Brazilian pepper, lead tree, melaleuca, Australian pine and melaleuca throughout 2,300 acres on the southern side of the base.  Invasive grasses were treated through foliar application, and the tree species were primarily treated through basal bark application to kill the plants in place.  Following the initial herbicide applications, contractors were responsible to retreat invasive plant species within the project area until the plants were completely dead.  No further removal or treatment was required after the invasive species were killed, and plants were left to breakdown over time.  In addition, mechanical clearing of Brazilian pepper was accomplished on a 30 acre site which included an area of gopher tortoise habitat in the south central portion of the base.  MacDill also accomplished a formal survey of invasive species coverage throughout the 2,300 wooded acres being managed for control of invasive species.
Habitat Description: Pine forest areas are largely historic planted pine which has not been managed for timber.  Areas of oak hammock and mangrove lined ditches are scattered throughout the pine areas and mangrove esturary predominates along the southern boundary of the site.  Additionally, there are large tracts of land within the site that have been historically disturbed (former landfill areas) which are highly invaded with Brazilian pepper.  Brazilian pepper, melaleuca, and lead tree are commonly found along the forest edges and scattered throughout the understory.  Open fields have scattered areas of cogan grass.
Project Benefits: Improve or protect water quality:Protect/improve/provide habitat for birds:Protect/improve/provide habitat for other wildlife
Partners: None

Project Description: The primary project goal is removal of the upland mounds throughout the site to restore historic hydrology. The mounds are being removed using the hydroblasting technique. Exotic vegetation on the mounds is removed and the mound material is spread in 360-degree direction using high pressure water jet. Each mound is reduced to an elevation below mean high water to eliminate the uplands and improve tidal flow. Once the mounds are reduced below mean high tides, they will be planted with smooth cord grass. Phase II of the project is currently being permitted as additional funding is already secured
Habitat Description: Extensive mangrove estuary that has been degraded through the construction of mosquito ditches, and creation of upland mounds.

Project Description: Chemical treatment of Brazilian pepper and other non-native, invasive species across two quadrants of the base (1,011 acres). Invasive trees and grasses were treated through a mixture of foliar application and girdling to kill the plants in place. Contractors were then responsible to retreat invasive plant species until the plants were dead. No further removal or treatment was required after the invasive species were killed, and plants were left to breakdown over time. The project area included 1,011 acres of upland forest and open fields (known as Quadrant 1, and Quadrant 2B). Mechanical clearing of live and dead Brazilian pepper was accomplished on a 10 acre site in Quadrant 3B.
Habitat Description: Pine forest areas are historic planted pine which has not been managed for timber. Areas of oak hammock and mangrove lined ditches are scattered throughout the pine areas and mangrove esturary predominates along the southern boundary of the site. Additionally, there are large tracts of land within the site that have been historically disturbed (former landfill areas) which are highly invaded with Brazilian pepper. Brazilian pepper, melaleuca, and lead tree are commonly found along the forest edges and scattered throughout the understory. Open fields have scattered areas of cogan grass.
Project Benefits: Improve or protect water quality:Protect/improve/provide habitat for birds

Project Description: Chemical treatment of all invasive species within the project area. Invasive trees and grasses were treated through a mixture of foliar application and girdling to kill the plants in place. Following the initial herbicide applications, contractors were responsible to retreat invasive plant species within the project area until the plants were completely dead. No further removal or treatment was required after the invasive species were killed, and plants were left to breakdown over time. The project area included 1,150 acres of upland forest and open fields (known as Quadrant 2 and Quadrant 3) bordered by a well maintained airfield to the north, mangrove estuary to the south and Quadrants 1 and 4 to the east and west, respectively.
Habitat Description: Pine forest areas are historic planted pine which has not been managed for timber. Areas of oak hammock and mangrove lined ditches are scattered throughout the pine areas and mangrove esturary predominates along the southern boundary of the site. Additionally, there are large tracts of land within the site that have been historically disturbed (former landfill areas) which are highly invaded with Brazilian pepper. Brazilian pepper, Melaleuca, and lead tree are commonly found along the forest edges and scattered throughout the understory. Open fields have scattered areas of cogan grass.

Project Description: The project dug up the mosquito ditch mounds, removing all of the vegetation including invasive species along a 1,200 foot length of historic mosquito ditch. A zone approximately 50 feet wide on both sides of the ditch was dug up to remove the mounds and vegetation. Most of the vegetation was chipped up, except for the largest oak trees and some palms which were set aside for re-use. Some of the fill was used to fill small sections of the mosquito ditch but the majority of the ditch as well as the mangroves along the ditch bank were not altered during restoration. The excess dirt was hauled off site and the disturbed areas of the site where the mosquito mounds were located (50 ft wide on each side of the ditch) were graded to a uniform elevation of +/- 2 feet amsl. This allows the entire site to be flooded during normal high tides. A 4:1 slope was created along the northern side of the site for the transition between wetlands and adjacent uplands. The large oak trees and palm trees removed earlier were placed back on the site (dead) to act as ‘structure’ or snags for additional habitat value. The western end of the mosquito ditch (outfall location of the ditch) was plugged to eliminate the potential for short-circuiting overland flow of freshwater (stormwater) during low tide conditions. Upon completion of site grading, the site was planted with 13,000 bare root marsh grass plants to help stabilize the sediment and create a marsh habitat. It is anticipated that mangrove (primarily Black) will recruit naturally across the site due to a large seed source in the surrounding areas.
Habitat Description: Mangrove wetlands consisting primarily of Black Mangroves and to a lesser extent Red Mangroves along the edges of the mosquito ditch. The mosquito ditch mounds throughout the site were heavily invaded by Brazilian pepper. The site lies adjacent to a mixed pine and hardwood upland system.
Project Benefits: Restore natural hydrology

Project Name: Oyster Reef Shoreline Stabilization Phase IV
Project Description: The project installed concrete oyster domes (reef balls) within the tidal flat zone approximately 50 feet seaward of the high tide line. Domes were placed base to base to create a solid substrate roughly 10 feet wide on which oysters could establish. The project constructed 1,890 linear feet of oyster reef using oyster domes (20,00 square feet in area) to protect approximately 1,600 linear feet of shoreline. Gaps were built into the reef to permit ingress/egress by marine life. The oyster reef helps reduce wave energy and trap sediment, eventually creating conditions suitable for establishment of salt marsh. A follow-on project will construct an additional 1,290 linear feet (4,300 square feet) of additional oyster habitat through the installation of 9,800 oyster shell bags. Eventually the site will be planted with marsh grass to further stabilize the eroding coastal system.
Habitat Description: A degraded coastal system undergoing severe erosion due to wind and waves. Habitat is primarily an open sand beach fronted by tidal flats and backed by a heavily eroded dune system (upland edge).
Project Benefits: Erosion control:Protect/improve/provide habitat for fish/shellfish
